  "text": "Previously we have studied the effect of topo II inhibition on plasmid DNA replication in Xenopus egg extracts. In the presence of replication intermediates show an excess of parental strand linkage (( þ )DLk) and highly catenated dimers accumulate (B1 catenane link per 200 base pairs (bp)), showing that topo II contributes to unlinking DNA during replication [CITATION_1] . There are two possible forms of ( þ )DLk on replication intermediates and, thus, two possible pathways for unlinking replicating DNA. The unreplicated portion may form ( þ ) supercoils, or the two replicated regions may wind around each other to form righthanded intertwinings. The latter will be trapped as ( þ ) catenanes if not removed before termination and are therefore called ( þ ) precatenanes [CITATION_2] . To determine whether topo II unlinks supercoils in front of the forks or precatenanes behind the forks, we trapped topo-II-cleavable complexes with VP-16 and mapped them with respect to replication forks by twodimensional (2D) gel electrophoresis. Cleavable complexes were detected only behind the replication forks, showing that topo II can unlink replicating DNA by precatenane removal [CITATION_3] . Nevertheless, the universality of the precatenane model is still open to discussion (supplementary information online).",
